    "body": "@nventuro: Hi\r\n\r\nI have recently come across the requirement to install OpenZeppelin code via `npm` (instead of manually copying all required source files, as I previously described in this thread).\r\n\r\nThis goes back to your suggestion.\r\nAt the time, I noted to you that Truffle had a \"hard time\" dealing with files outside of the `contracts` folder.\r\n\r\nHowever, I would like to correct that description of mine, as `truffle compile` works just fine.\r\nAll I need to change is the relative path that I use for importing OpenZeppelin files in my contracts (prepending it with `../node_modules/openzeppelin-solidity/contracts`).\r\n\r\nIt is in fact that Solidity compiler (`solc`) which cannot deal with \"external\" files.\r\n\r\nNow, `solc` has a compilation switch called `--allow-paths`, which is supposed to allow one to import files from outside the working folder.\r\nUnfortunately, this switch is currently not functioning correctly, and `solc` keeps throwing multiple \"File outside of allowed directories\" errors, regardless of the value that you set it to.\r\n\r\nI am working in collaboration with a contributor in order to resolve this (see [here](https://github.com/ethereum/solidity/issues/2742#issuecomment-426240873)), but until it is fixed, I have been wondering:\r\nHow do other people compile and deploy their contracts? Does everybody do it with Truffle?\r\nBecause clearly, if they use the Solidity compiler, then they must copy OpenZeppelin files into their project, in the same way that I do it.\r\n\r\nWould you know of any way to combine the installation of OpenZeppelin via `npm`, and the compilation of the contracts via `solc`?\r\n\r\nThanks",
