    "body": "@nventuro:\r\n\r\nThank you for your quick response.\r\n\r\nI use:\r\n1. `truffle test` (preceded by `truffle compile`) along with `ganache-cli` for testing.\r\n2. `solidity-coverage` along with `testrpc-sc` for a full coverage report.\r\n3. The output of `solc` (abi and bin files) for contract-deployment and contract-interaction via web3.js v1.x directly (in opposed to the previous two, where web3.js v0.x is used indirectly).\r\n\r\nFor #1 and #2, I even implemented a NodeJS script which starts the Ethereum node (either `ganache-cli` or `testrpc-sc`) and then runs the test (either  `truffle test` or `solidity-coverage`). The script is connected in the `package.json` file, so all I need to do after installation is `npm test 1` or `npm test 2`.\r\nThis script also has the advantage of being OS-agnostic (platform-independent).\r\n\r\nWhy did I choose to use `solc` for the actual deployment and interaction?\r\n\r\nWell, first and foremost because it generates bin and abi files, while Truffle generates json files.\r\nAnd since I would ultimately need to publish the abi files, I figured I may as well go along with `solc` for this purpose.\r\nSomeone insinuated to me earlier today that I could extract bin and abi from the json, but why should I bother with having to \"auto-script\" that?\r\n\r\nSecond, as you mentioned, Truffle testing relies on the Mocha framework. I could use it also for contract interaction, but that's not the purpose of Mocha, is it?\r\nTruffle deployment (via `truffle deploy` or `truffle migrate`) does allow me to deploy the contracts without going via the Mocha framework. However, I have found their deployment syntax to be very cumbersome, and not very convenient for use.\r\n\r\nThird, Truffle is still stuck on web3.js v0.18.4 for some reason.\r\n\r\nFourth, AFAIK, the development of `solc` has forked at some point from the initial branch which targeted Windows an Ubuntu, to a branch which targets MacOS.\r\nSo while using Truffle leaves me \"in the dark\" about which compiler is used for compiling my code, using `solc` doesn't (I download an explicit version for my OS).\r\nOf course, this is not ideal, since I am possibly testing my contracts with one compiler version, and then deploying them with another.\r\nBut this way, at least I know exactly how my deployed code was compiled.\r\nAlso, `truffle compile` yields a different output when executed twice on the same input, which makes it hard for me to track changes in the binaries.\r\n",
